  {
    "id": 1621359391868,
    "type": "text",
    "content": "\"<h1>Condition</h1>\""
  },
  {
    "id": 1636662065710,
    "type": "grid",
    "content": [
      [
        {
          "id": 1636662074274,
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\"<h2>Live Hard Coral Cover</h2><p>Most coral reef monitoring within Australia has been conducted on the GBR, which includes 85% of the country’s coral reefs, and data are available for multiple time periods for most sites. Between 1994 and 1999 live hard coral cover across Australia declined slightly from 35.2% to 34.5%. Subsequently, large scale coral bleaching events in Australia in 1998 and one more focused on the GBR in 2002 caused hard coral cover to decline to 30.6% by 2003. Substantial recovery occurred during the next four years, with average coral cover reaching 35.4% in 2007. However, between 2008 and 2014, coral cover declined to 27.4%, due to tropical cyclones, the initial stages of a crown-of-thorns starfish outbreak on the GBR and coral bleaching on reefs in Western Australia. This was followed by two years of recovery, however, back-to-back coral bleaching events in 2016 and 2017 resulted in a decline to the lowest coral cover in the record by 2018 (25.7%) and slight recovery by 2019 (to 26.0%).<span style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\\\">&nbsp;</span></p>\""
        }
      ],
      [
        {
          "id": 1636662077004,
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\"<h2>Algae Cover</h2><p><span style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\\\">The trend in the cover of algae on Australian&nbsp;coral reefs during the last 25 years was generally the inverse of coral cover. In 1994, average cover of algae was 21.2%&nbsp;and&nbsp;increased only slightly over&nbsp;the next five years.&nbsp;Beginning in 1999, while coral cover declined in response to bleaching events, the cover of algae&nbsp;increased substantially,&nbsp;reaching 28.5% in 2003.&nbsp;As coral reefs recovered between 2004 and&nbsp;2008, the cover of algae decreased to 24.5%.&nbsp;From 2008, algal cover has generally increased, with some fluctuations, and substantial&nbsp;increases in 2017 and 2018, peaking at 39.2%, linked to coral decline after bleaching events.&nbsp;In 2019, the average cover of algae was 37.5%,&nbsp;which equates to&nbsp;77% more algae on Australian reefs&nbsp;than was present in&nbsp;1994.&nbsp;</span></p>\""
        }
      ]
    ]
  },
